Finally, as to punishments and penalties‚ fines were imposed⁷ and im- prisonment and chastisement inflicted without definite restriction. But in view of the extra-legal character of its procedure, the council acted in these matters with marked caution. Although the limitation as to life and limb, desired by parliament, failed to be enacted in the statutes, the council never failed to observe it. Only one of our cases (p. 104) men- tions such a thing as the pillory. The penalties threatened in the subpoena and other instruments were theoretical‚ to be understood as an intimation of the seriousness of the matter in hand, and never literally exacted. Fines were usually in the form of amerciaments, being adjusted not in proportion to the offenee but whatever could feasibly be exacted in return for a pardon or release. Imprisonments were indeterminate, “ until it is otherwise ordered.” The Fleet was the prison particularly used by the council and the chancery.
